Date:  0/0/1966
Source:  English Language in Aust. & NZ, The
Author:  TURNER
Vol / Page:  135
Edition:
Quote:  In New Zealand the word <i>Maori</i> sometimes enters into slang with contemptuous connotation but there is a good-natured tolerance, even tinged with envy for an admirable adjustment to life's problems, in a term like <i>Maori P.T.</i> (from the army P T = physical training) to mean lying down and doing nothing, what the Australian calls <i>spinebashing. </i>
